        <p>Climate change is one of the defining challenges of our time. It refers to long-term shifts in temperature, weather patterns, and ecosystems, driven primarily by human activities such as burning fossil fuels, deforestation, and industrial agriculture. These activities release greenhouse gases—especially carbon dioxide and methane—into the atmosphere, trapping heat and warming the planet. </p>
        <p>The effects of this warming are already visible. Average global temperatures are rising, glaciers and ice sheets are melting, and sea levels are creeping upward, threatening coastal communities. Extreme weather events—heatwaves, droughts, floods, and stronger storms—are becoming more frequent and intense. These changes disrupt food systems, strain water supplies, damage infrastructure, and increase health risks, particularly for the most vulnerable populations.</p>
        <p>Climate change is not only an environmental issue; it is also an economic, social, and ethical one. Communities that have contributed the least to greenhouse gas emissions often face the greatest consequences, raising questions of fairness and responsibility. At the same time, the costs of inaction continue to grow, while the benefits of addressing climate change—cleaner air, new jobs in renewable energy, healthier ecosystems—are substantial. <br>
            Addressing climate change requires both mitigation and adaptation. Mitigation involves reducing emissions by transitioning to renewable energy, improving energy efficiency, protecting forests, and rethinking how we produce and consume goods. Adaptation focuses on preparing for unavoidable impacts, such as building resilient infrastructure, improving disaster response, and developing climate-resilient agriculture. <br>
            While the scale of the problem is daunting, solutions exist. Governments, businesses, communities, and individuals all have roles to play. Climate change is ultimately a test of global cooperation and long-term thinking—how we choose to act today will shape the planet future generations inherit.
        </p>
        <h5>An overview of the causes, consequences, and urgent actions needed to address climate change worldwide.</h5>
        <p>Climate change also affects the natural systems that sustain life on Earth. Oceans, which absorb much of the excess heat and carbon dioxide, are warming and becoming more acidic. This threatens coral reefs, fisheries, and the livelihoods of millions of people who depend on the sea for food and income. On land, shifting temperatures and rainfall patterns are altering habitats, pushing many plant and animal species toward extinction and reducing biodiversity that ecosystems rely on to remain resilient. <br>
            Human health is increasingly at risk as well. Rising temperatures worsen air pollution and increase heat-related illnesses and deaths. Changes in climate expand the range of disease-carrying insects such as mosquitoes, contributing to the spread of illnesses like malaria and dengue fever. Food insecurity is also likely to grow as crop yields decline in some regions due to heat stress, droughts, or unpredictable weather. <br>
            Importantly, climate change is deeply connected to how societies are organized. Urban design, transportation systems, energy choices, and consumption habits all influence emissions. Cities that invest in public transit, green spaces, and energy-efficient buildings can significantly reduce their carbon footprint while improving quality of life. Similarly, supporting sustainable agriculture and reducing food waste can lower emissions and protect natural resources.</p>
        <p>Education and public awareness play a critical role. Understanding the science behind climate change helps counter misinformation and empowers people to make informed choices. Youth movements, Indigenous leadership, and grassroots activism have become powerful forces, pushing climate action higher on political and corporate agendas and reminding decision-makers of their responsibility to the future. <br>
            Ultimately, climate change challenges humanity to rethink its relationship with the planet. It calls for a shift from short-term exploitation to long-term stewardship. The decisions made in the coming decades will determine not only environmental outcomes, but also global stability, equity, and the well-being of generations to come.</p>
